00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:57.000
OK. So, let's dive right in.
The discovery of the transforming

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:04.000
principle. It's a
wonderfully old-fashioned

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
kind of word. Nobody would
use language like this today.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
The discovery of the
transforming principle. So,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
this starts, this shaggy dog story
starts in about 1928 with the work

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
of Griffiths. Griffiths had no
particular interest in DNA or

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
genetics or biochemistry
for that matter.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Griffith was interested in bacteria.
He wanted to understand bacteria.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And, in particular, he
studied pneumococcus bacteria,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
which could infect and kill mice.
And he was very interested in the

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.000
mechanism by with these
pneumococci could kill mice.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Now, it turns out that the
pneumococcus bacteria came in two

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
different types.
One, the bacteria,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
when they grew on a Petri plate,
produced a glistening, smooth, shiny

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:14.000
colony. We'll call them
smooth bacteria here.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
And these bacteria, in
addition to being smooth and

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
glistening, were virulent.
That is, if you inject into the

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
mouse, these bacteria would kill the
mouse. They are smooth because they

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:33.000
have this encapsulating
polysaccharide coat around them.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
And it's not necessarily the case
that that's what makes them virulent,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
although it actually does have a
role in that, but it is the case

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
that they're smooth and
they're virulent. So,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
you inject in a mouse, mouse
dies because the mouse is not

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
resistant to these bacteria. By
contrast, there were strains of

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
pneumococcus that were rough.
They did not have the same kind of

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
a polysaccharide coat, and
therefore they had a very rough

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
appearance. They
didn't glisten.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And these were non-virulent. If
you inject these into the mouse,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
the mouse immune system was able
to fight these particular rough

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:19.000
bacteria. OK. So,
Griffith did the obvious

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
experiments. So,
take some bacteria,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:30.000
we'll take some smooth
virulent bacteria, we'll inject

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
into a mouse. And
what will happen?

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:43.000
The mouse will die. This is one of
the easier assays in the laboratory.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.000
It's the feet up, feet down
assay, you have a dead mouse.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:57.000
OK. Number two. Then
take the rough bacteria,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:05.000
inject it into a
mouse, what happens?

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Sorry? It lives. The mouse
lives because these are

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
non virulent. OK. Now,
let's just do some simple

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
controls. Let's take the smooth
bacteria and autoclave them,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.000
heat them up to very high
temperature to kill them.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.000
How will we know they're dead?
You try plating them out. They

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:32.000
don't grow anymore,
so they're dead.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:37.000
So, take heat killed, and
you can verify in the lab that

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:43.000
they're killed,
heat killed smooth,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.000
check that they really were heat
killed, inject them into the mouse.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And what happens? It lives
because, I mean, they're bacteria,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
right? OK. Last of all we take the
utterly harmless rough bacteria,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
plus the utterly harmless
heat-killed smooth bacteria,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
we inject them into the
mouse, and what happens?

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:18.000
It dies. That is a notable result
because the rough bacteria alone

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:24.000
will not kill this mouse and the
smooth bacteria that have been

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.000
heat-killed will not kill this mouse,
but together they killed the mouse.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:37.000
This is very puzzling. What
was even more puzzling was

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:44.000
when you autopsied the mouse,
you can isolate from that mouse

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:52.000
smooth, virulent, live
bacteria, but you didn't put

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:59.000
any in. Very strange. So,
this actually yields live

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:07.000
smooth virulent bacteria despite
not having put any in there.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:12.000
Virulent bacteria. Somehow
we were able to create

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.000
smooth and virulent bacteria
notwithstanding not having put any

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:22.000
in here. So, of course,
Griffith then attempted to say,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:28.000
well, what was it that
allowed this to happen?

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So, he could try putting in dead
rough bacteria with dead smooth

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
bacteria. That doesn't do anything.
You need to have something alive.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So, you've got to have live rough
bacteria. You can then say let me

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
take the dead virulent bacteria and
start fractionating it biochemically

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
and asking what fraction of that
material from the dead bacteria

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
allows us to recover, to have
this property of being able

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
to now produce virulent
bacteria that killed the mice?

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
And do you realize how utterly
tedious and painful that

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
experiment is? You
take the dead bacteria,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
you fractionate it into lots of
different biochemical fractions.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
For each fraction, how do you
test whether it has the property?

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
You've got to shoot up a bunch
of mice. This is a very tedious

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
procedure. I mean it is, you
know, you can't underestimate

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
how important the assay is, how
important it is to come up with

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
easy ways to do things in order
to be able to accelerate progress.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Griffith tried hard and roughly
began to purify fractions and get

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
information about what the
fractions were. But, in fact,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
this work really never did
lead to a clear conclusion.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
But it did tell people that
there was some material,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
which got named The Transforming
Principle. This is almost like an

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
old alchemical kind of word,
a principle being a particular

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
chemical composition of matter,
which if you don't know what it is

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
you call it The Living
Principle or something like that.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So, what was this
transforming principle?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Well, it really took work
about 15 years later by Avery,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:15.000
McCarty and MacLeod to sort this out.
What Avery, McCarty and MacLeod did

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:23.000
was the same experiment
basically, except minus the mice.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:30.000
What they found was you
could take the dead bacteria,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:37.000
combine it, the dead virulent
bacteria, the dead smooth bacteria,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:45.000
combine it with the live rough
bacteria, and by combining it in the

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:52.000
right way in a test tube you would
be able to plate it out on a Petri

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:00.000
plate and see smooth
bacteria come out.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Sans mouse. So, they
didn't need the mouse.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
This dramatically accelerated work
because if you're able to just take

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
fractions of the dead bacteria,
add it to the live bacteria and look

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
for the presence of some smooth
bacteria coming out of it,

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
you would be able to work much
more quickly. And they did.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And they began purifying. And
they began purifying and they

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
tried to isolate the fraction that
contained this new ability to make

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
these bacteria acquire a new
property. And they knew that they

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
were transforming the
heredity of this bacterium.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:34.000
They were transforming the
traits of this bacterium.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:38.000
They were, in fact,
transmitting heredity.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And they purified and purified
and purified. And eventually,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
testing many, many fractions and
making them purer and purer and

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.000
purer and purer, they
found that consistently the

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
fraction that contained heredity
was the fraction that contained DNA.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Now, it was a lot more work than
that because no fraction is pure.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
DNA is in multiple
fractions. But, you know,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.000
they kept trying to purify
it. And it sure looked like the

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.000
transforming principle. The
property of being able to

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:16.000
transform was co-purifying
along with the DNA fraction.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
And you know what the
reaction to that was? Well,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:25.000
mostly it was that they must have
goofed because all smart right

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:30.000
thinking people knew that DNA
was an absolutely boring molecule.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Because the interesting molecule
at this time was proteins.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Everybody knew there were zillions,
there were 20 amino acids, they came

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
in zillions of combinations,
they had all sorts of different

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
shapes and properties, and
hydrophobic ones, hydrophilic

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
ones that are enzymes. And,
clearly, anything as important

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
as heredity was not going to be
encoded in some utterly boring

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
structural molecule that was just
a long polymer of four virtually

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
identical units. And so,
the sort of reaction was

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
this is interesting but
there must be some trick,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
something must be wrong in
this experiment, give or take.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
Now, why did people think
that DNA was so boring?

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Now, DNA had been known for
a long time, since the 1860s.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
Lots of molecules were known, but
why was DNA boring and why were

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
proteins kind of exciting? So,
for that, we really do have to

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
look some more closely
at the structure of DNA.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I want to review the structure of
DNA here because we're going to use

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.000
it a lot. So, DNA
has three components,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:32.000
as you undoubtedly know.
It has first a sugar,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:43.000
or almost sugar, two prime
deoxyribose, two prime deoxyribose,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:54.000
so it's a pentose, or almost the
deoxypentose. And its structure,

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:03.000
and this is an important structure.
In order to be a true sugar,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:10.000
to be ribose you would have a
hydroxyl. Deoxyribose just has a

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:16.000
hydrogen there. And the
way we number these carbons

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:23.000
around this five carbon sugar are
very important and we'll always talk

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:30.000
about them, the one prime, two
prime, three prime, four prime

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:37.000
and five prime carbons
of this deoxyribose.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And you'll notice that it's the
two prime carbon that is dioxi.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.000
So, that's the sugar. The next
important component as we build up

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:54.000
DNA is the base, OK?
The base is put here.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.000
Now, I'm going to start
simplifying our sugar.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:15.000
Base. So, there are four kinds
of bases that can go here.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And they are adenine,
guanine, thymine, cytosine.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:38.000
So, that's the second important
part of building up DNA.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:47.000
The third important part in
building up DNA is to make the

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:55.000
monomers that are used to
produce DNA, we need to put on

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:07.000
a triphosphate. And he we
go. We'll take our sugar

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:22.000
here, our base over here, and
then off this carbon we have our

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:35.000
phosphate. And we
have a triphosphate.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:46.000
There we go. So, this is the
monomer that is used to build up DNA.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:58.000
This guy here is called
a nucleoside, note the S.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
This guy here with the triphosphate
on it is called a nucleotide.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:07.000
It's not usually written with
such a big capital letter,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.000
but nonetheless I point this
out. And, obviously, what is this

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:17.000
triphosphate going to do for us?
It's going to provide the energy to

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.000
allow us to make DNA polymer chains.
We're going to do a dehydration

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.000
synthesis where we break two of
those phosphates off and use it for

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:32.000
the energy to be able to
catalyze DNA chains to be made.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:40.000
OK. Now, when you combine
nucleotides into a DNA strand you do

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:48.000
so to create a sugar phosphate
backbone. And you'll see for many

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:56.000
molecules, I don't care that
you know their structures

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:04.000
terribly well. But for
the basic structure of DNA,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:12.000
including its sugar phosphate
backbone, it's going to be important

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:21.000
for all that we talk about. So,
what happens is we have a chain

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:30.000
of DNA growing like this,
and we have our OH here.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
We have our base here.
And which carbon is this?

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Five prime, that's right. OK.
Which carbon is this? This one.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Great. That's the three
prime, two prime, one prime.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Great. OK. To this three prime
carbon we add this triphosphate

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:05.000
breaking off two phosphates there.
The diphosphate gets broken off,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:17.000
the pyrophosphate. And we get a
single phosphate linkage to the next

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:29.000
subunit of the chain.
So, here we go phosphate,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:37.000
sugar, phosphate, sugar.
And if we ignore these bases,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.000
which, you know, who cares about the
bases anyway, what we have is just

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
phosphate, sugar,
phosphate, sugar, phosphate,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:50.000
sugar, phosphate, sugar. OK?
So, it's a very simple structure.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:54.000
There's nothing hard to remember
about this. And the phosphate is

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
always attached to the three prime
carbon of the preceding sugar and to

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:03.000
the five prime carbon
of the next sugar.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
OK? So, we often speak of chains of
DNA growing from the five prime end

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:10.000
to the three prime end. And
that confuses non-molecular

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:13.000
biologists to no end.
What are we talking about,

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:17.000
five prime ends and three prime ends?
This is what we're talking about.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:20.000
But the additions are catalyzed
onto the three prime carbon of that

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:24.000
sugar. It grows at it three
prime end. So, you have sugar,

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
phosphate, sugar, phosphate,
sugar, phosphate. So, that's it.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:33.000
We're all done. Well,
there are the bases,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:41.000
I guess, too, right? So,
we'll mention these bases.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:48.000
The bases are, they come in
two types. There are purines.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Adenine and guanine are purines.
And there's a six member rings with

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:02.000
a five member ring. And
there are two bases that are

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:07.000
