00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:16.000
Pretty amazing stuff. So,
last point I want to touch on,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:23.000
and I'm not sure I'll get to,
get all the way there, but this

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:29.000
model, this model here of DNA coming
apart and each strand serving as a

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:36.000
template for the other strand
is called Semi-Conservative

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:43.000
Replication. That is
one strand is used as the

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:50.000
template for the other strand,
so there's an old strand and a new

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:57.000
strand that's made. In
theory, you could imagine that

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:05.000
DNA replication
occurred not like this.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:09.000
But instead somehow, I can't
imagine how, but you could

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:14.000
imagine, and people were willing
to imagine it, that the old strands

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:18.000
stayed together but somehow became
a template for making a new double

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:23.000
helix without actually using them.
This model of the strands actually

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:27.000
serving as a template would predict
that each new DNA double helix was,

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:32.000
in fact, composed of one
old and one new strand.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:36.000
If you could prove that then you'd
have real confirmation of this Crick

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:40.000
Watson model, semi-conservative
replication. And so,

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:44.000
a young student, two young students,
Matt Meselson, who's still working

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:48.000
and is down the road at
Harvard and a wonderful person,

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:52.000
and Frank Stahl, who's still working
in Oregon, proved that the new DNAs

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:56.000
that were made after each
generation were, in fact,

00:48:56.000 --> 00:49:00.000
composed of one old
strand and one new strand.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:06.000
How could you possibly do that?
Sorry? Radioactive labeling. But

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:12.000
how do you radioactively label
it so that you can see that it's,

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:18.000
that you've got a double helix
that's half one and half the other?

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:24.000
Old ones labeled with, well, with
one isotope. It actually turns out

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:30.000
to be nitrogen. The new
one with a new isotope.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:34.000
Say N14. You can do heavy
nitrogen and ordinary nitrogen.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:38.000
And if what you could do is grow up
your DNA, when you first grow it in

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:42.000
normal nitrogen,
then you shift to N15,

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:46.000
heavy nitrogen, you could make
DNA molecules that were half old,

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:50.000
half new, and therefore half
labeled with normal nitrogen,

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:54.000
half labeled with heavy nitrogen.
And how would I prove that these

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:58.000
DNA molecules were a 50/50 hybrid?
What would be the property that I

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:02.000
would be able to test? Well,
radioactivity turns out to be

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:06.000
really hard to weight density.
It turns out density, if I could

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:10.000
just measure the density of the
DNA, I would show that if the

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:14.000
semi-conservative model is
true, the molecules will now have

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:19.000
intermediate density between
all heavy and all light nitrogen.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:23.000
They had to work out a
centrifugation technique so

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:27.000
sensitive, a salt gradient
centrifugation where you could put

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:32.000
